# âœ… What is Reacting to Events?

ğŸ‘‰ When user clicks
ğŸ‘‰ When user types
ğŸ‘‰ When form submits

React runs a function.

Thatâ€™s called **event handling**.

---

# ğŸ§  Basic Flow

```
User Action (Click / Type)
        â†“
Event Triggered
        â†“
Function Executes
        â†“
UI Updates (if state changes)
```

---

# âœ… 1ï¸âƒ£ Click Event Example

## Simple Button Click

```jsx
import React from "react";

function MyComponent() {

  function handleClick() {
    alert("Button Clicked ğŸš€");
  }

  return (
    <div>
      <button onClick={handleClick}>
        Click Me
      </button>
    </div>
  );
}

export default MyComponent;
```

---

### ğŸ”¥ Important

Notice this:

```jsx
onClick={handleClick}
```

âœ… Correct
âŒ Wrong â†’ `onClick={handleClick()}`

Because:

* `handleClick` â†’ pass function
* `handleClick()` â†’ immediately execute

---

# âœ… 2ï¸âƒ£ Using useState (Update UI on Click)

Now letâ€™s make it dynamic.

```jsx
import React, { useState } from "react";

function Counter() {

  const [count, setCount] = useState(0);

  function increase() {
    setCount(count + 1);
  }

  return (
    <div>
      <h2>Count: {count}</h2>
      <button onClick={increase}>Increase</button>
    </div>
  );
}

export default Counter;
```

---

## ğŸ” Flow

```
Button Click
     â†“
increase() runs
     â†“
setCount()
     â†“
State changes
     â†“
Component re-renders
     â†“
Updated count shown
```

---

# âœ… 3ï¸âƒ£ Handling Input Change

```jsx
import React, { useState } from "react";

function InputExample() {

  const [name, setName] = useState("");

  function handleChange(event) {
    setName(event.target.value);
  }

  return (
    <div>
      <input 
        type="text" 
        onChange={handleChange} 
      />
      <p>Hello {name}</p>
    </div>
  );
}

export default InputExample;
```

---

## ğŸ”¥ Important Concept

`event` object contains:

```
event.target.value
```

That is what user typed.

---

# âœ… 4ï¸âƒ£ Form Submit Event

```jsx
import React, { useState } from "react";

function FormExample() {

  const [email, setEmail] = useState("");

  function handleSubmit(event) {
    event.preventDefault();   // prevents page reload
    alert("Submitted: " + email);
  }

  return (
    <form onSubmit={handleSubmit}>
      <input 
        type="email"
        onChange={(e) => setEmail(e.target.value)}
      />
      <button type="submit">Submit</button>
    </form>
  );
}

export default FormExample;
```

---

# ğŸ¯ Most Common React Events

| Event       | Usage          |
| ----------- | -------------- |
| onClick     | Button click   |
| onChange    | Input change   |
| onSubmit    | Form submit    |
| onMouseOver | Mouse hover    |
| onKeyDown   | Keyboard press |

---

# ğŸ§  Final Big Picture

React event handling is:

```
HTML Event
     +
JavaScript Function
     +
State Update
     =
Interactive UI
```

