Good Venky ğŸ‘Œ
Now letâ€™s understand **Passing Custom Arguments to Event Functions in React** in a very simple flow.

---

# ğŸ§  Normal Event Function (No Arguments)

```jsx
function handleClick() {
  console.log("Button clicked");
}

<button onClick={handleClick}>Click Me</button>
```

When button is clicked â†’ `handleClick()` runs.

---

# ğŸ”µ Problem

What if you want to pass a custom value?

Example:

ğŸ‘‰ When clicking button
ğŸ‘‰ Send `"Venky"` to function

Like this:

```js
handleClick("Venky")
```

You CANNOT do this:

```jsx
<button onClick={handleClick("Venky")}>Click</button>
```

âŒ This runs immediately when component renders
Not when button is clicked.

---

# âœ… Correct Way â€“ Using Arrow Function

```jsx
function handleClick(name) {
  console.log("Hello " + name);
}

<button onClick={() => handleClick("Venky")}>
  Click Me
</button>
```

---

## ğŸ” Flow

1ï¸âƒ£ Button clicked
2ï¸âƒ£ Arrow function runs
3ï¸âƒ£ It calls `handleClick("Venky")`
4ï¸âƒ£ Console â†’ Hello Venky

---

# ğŸ”µ Example 2 â€“ Passing ID

Very common in real projects.

```jsx
function deleteUser(id) {
  console.log("Deleting user with id:", id);
}

<button onClick={() => deleteUser(101)}>
  Delete
</button>
```

---

# ğŸ”µ Example 3 â€“ Inside Map (Very Important ğŸ”¥)

```jsx
const users = [
  { id: 1, name: "Venky" },
  { id: 2, name: "Rahul" }
];

function showUser(id) {
  console.log("User ID:", id);
}

function App() {
  return (
    <div>
      {users.map((user) => (
        <button 
          key={user.id}
          onClick={() => showUser(user.id)}
        >
          {user.name}
        </button>
      ))}
    </div>
  );
}
```

When you click:

* Venky â†’ prints 1
* Rahul â†’ prints 2

---

# ğŸ§  Why We Use Arrow Function?

Because:

```jsx
onClick={handleClick("Venky")}
```

means:

ğŸ‘‰ Execute immediately

But:

```jsx
onClick={() => handleClick("Venky")}
```

means:

ğŸ‘‰ Execute ONLY when clicked

---

# âš¡ Extra Important (Event + Custom Argument)

If you also want event object:

```jsx
function handleClick(event, name) {
  console.log(event);
  console.log(name);
}

<button onClick={(event) => handleClick(event, "Venky")}>
  Click
</button>
```

---

# ğŸ¯ Simple Rule

If passing argument:

```
onClick={() => functionName(value)}
```

Without argument:

```
onClick={functionName}
```

